  "name": "wordpress_theme_design",
  "type": "code/html",
  "content": "Let's begin by setting up the basic structure of your WordPress theme. We'll create the theme's necessary files step-by-step, starting with the core elements. We'll start by creating a new folder for your theme, and then create the `style.css` and `index.php` files. These files are the foundation for any WordPress theme.

### Step 1: Create the Theme Directory and Basic Files

1. **Create a Theme Directory**: Navigate to the `/wp-content/themes/` folder of your WordPress installation. Create a new folder here for your theme, let's call it `custom-landing-page`.

2. **Create the `style.css` File**:
   The `style.css` file provides the basic information WordPress needs to recognize your theme. It also contains the custom styles we will add for designing your theme.

   Create a new file called `style.css` in your theme folder (`custom-landing-page`), and add the following code to define the theme:

   ```css
   /*
    Theme Name: Custom Landing Page
    Theme URI: http://example.com/
    Author: Your Name
    Author URI: http://example.com/
    Description: A custom landing page theme for WordPress
    Version: 1.0
    License: GNU General Public License v2 or later
    License URI: http://www.gnu.org/licenses/gpl-2.0.html
    Text Domain: custom-landing-page
   */

   /* Reset some default styles */
   * {
     margin: 0;
     padding: 0;
     box-sizing: border-box;
   }

   body {
     font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
     line-height: 1.6;
     background-color: #f9f9f9;
     color: #333;
   }

   header {
     display: flex;
     align-items: center;
     background-color: #0044cc;
     padding: 10px;
   }

   header img.logo {
     height: 50px;
     margin-right: 20px;
   }

   nav.menu {
     display: flex;
     gap: 20px;
   }

   nav.menu a {
     color: white;
     text-decoration: none;
     transition: color 0.3s;
   }

   nav.menu a:hover {
     color: #ffcc00;
   }
   ```

   This stylesheet will give your header a basic design with colors and hover effects for the navigation menu items.

3. **Create the `index.php` File**:
   The `index.php` file is the main template file for the theme. For now, we will create a simple version that displays the header and a placeholder for the content of the landing page.

   Create a new file called `index.php` in the `custom-landing-page` folder, and add the following code:

   ```php
   <?php
   /**
    * Main Template File
    *
    * @package Custom Landing Page
    */

   get_header();
   ?>

   <div class="background-section">
     <div class="background-graphic">
       <h1>Welcome to Our Company</h1>
       <p>Your journey to success starts here.</p>
     </div>
   </div>

   <div class="content-section">
     <p>Here you can add more sections of text and graphics as needed.</p>
   </div>

   <?php
   get_footer();
   ?>
   ```

   The `index.php` file serves as the core template that will include the header, content sections, and footer. The call to `get_header()` includes the header file, which we will create next.

### Step 2: Create the `header.php` File

Next, we will create the `header.php` file that will be included at the top of your pages. This file will contain the company logo, a navigation menu, and some basic styling for a mobile-friendly header.

Create a new file called `header.php` in the `custom-landing-page` folder, and add the following code:

```php
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html <?php language_attributes(); ?>>
<head>
   <meta charset="<?php bloginfo( 'charset' ); ?>">
   <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">
   <link rel="stylesheet" href="<?php echo esc_url( get_stylesheet_uri() ); ?>">
   <?php wp_head(); ?>
</head>
<body <?php body_class(); ?>>
   <header>
     <img src="<?php echo esc_url( get_template_directory_uri() . '/images/logo.png' ); ?>" alt="Company Logo" class="logo">
     <nav class="menu">
       <?php
         wp_nav_menu( array(
           'theme_location' => 'main-menu',
           'container' => '',
           'menu_class' => ''
         ));
       ?>
     </nav>
   </header>
```

This file includes the header structure for your website and integrates WordPress functionality like `wp_nav_menu` to dynamically load the navigation menu.

### Step 3: Register the Menu in `functions.php`

Now, we need to register the navigation menu so that WordPress knows it should be used for the `main-menu` location. Let's create a `functions.php` file in your theme folder.

Create `functions.php` in the `custom-landing-page` folder and add the following code:

```php
<?php
/**
 * Theme Functions
 *
 * @package Custom Landing Page
 */

function custom_landing_page_setup() {
   // Register the main menu
   register_nav_menus( array(
     'main-menu' => __( 'Main Menu', 'custom-landing-page' )
   ));
}
add_action( 'after_setup_theme', 'custom_landing_page_setup' );
```

This function will register the navigation menu for use in your header.

### Next Steps

1. **Add the Footer File**: Create a `footer.php` file that will be used for the footer section.
2. **Add JavaScript** for mobile menu toggling if needed.
3. **Customize the Landing Page**: Add additional styles and sections to make the landing page more attractive.

Would you like me to continue with creating the footer and mobile toggle functionality next, or do you have any specific requirements to discuss further?"}

