Yes, it's possible to replace the JavaScript functionality for the mobile menu toggle with pure CSS using the checkbox hack. This approach uses a hidden checkbox input to control the visibility of the menu. Let me update the code to use CSS only.

### Step 1: Update `header.php` File
Replace the JavaScript-based toggle button with an input checkbox that will serve as the trigger.

```php
<header>
  <img src="<?php echo esc_url( get_template_directory_uri() . '/images/logo.png' ); ?>" alt="Company Logo" class="logo">
  <input type="checkbox" id="menu-toggle" class="menu-toggle-checkbox" />
  <label for="menu-toggle" class="menu-toggle-label">
    <span class="menu-icon">&#9776;</span>
  </label>
  <nav class="menu" id="primary-menu">
    <?php
      wp_nav_menu( array(
        'theme_location' => 'main-menu',
        'container' => '',
        'menu_class' => ''
      ));
    ?>
  </nav>
</header>
```

### Step 2: Update the CSS in `style.css`
Update the CSS to use the checkbox to control the visibility of the menu:

```css
.menu-toggle-checkbox {
  display: none;
}

.menu-toggle-label {
  display: none;
  background: none;
  border: none;
  color: white;
  font-size: 2rem;
  cursor: pointer;
}

.menu {
  display: flex;
  gap: 20px;
}

@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .menu {
    display: none;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 10px;
    background-color: #0044cc;
    padding: 10px;
  }

  .menu-toggle-label {
    display: block;
  }

  .menu-toggle-checkbox:checked + .menu-toggle-label + .menu {
    display: flex;
  }
}
```

### Explanation
- **Checkbox Hack**: The checkbox (`menu-toggle-checkbox`) is hidden by default, but is used to track the open/closed state of the menu.
- **Label as Toggle Button**: The label (`menu-toggle-label`) is styled to look like a hamburger button. Clicking on it will check/uncheck the checkbox.
- **CSS to Show Menu**: When the checkbox is checked (`menu-toggle-checkbox:checked`), the adjacent sibling menu (`+ .menu`) is displayed.

This approach ensures that you can toggle the menu without any JavaScript, relying solely on HTML and CSS.

Would you like to proceed with testing this CSS-only solution or work on adding more sections to the landing page?

